<p>LSTM, which is a successful method for NLP applications [
 <xref rid="pone.0233126.ref028" ref-type="bibr">28</xref>, 
 <xref rid="pone.0233126.ref029" ref-type="bibr">29</xref>], processes a sequence of input and target pairs [(
 <italic>x</italic>
 <sub>1</sub>, 
 <italic>y</italic>
 <sub>1</sub>), …, (
 <italic>x</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>n</italic>
 </sub>, 
 <italic>y</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>n</italic>
 </sub>)]. For each pair, it takes a new input 
 <italic>x</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>i</italic>
 </sub> and produces an estimate for a target 
 <italic>y</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>i</italic>
 </sub> using earlier inputs 
 <italic>x</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>i</italic>−
  <italic>t</italic>
 </sub>, …, 
 <italic>x</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>i</italic>
 </sub>. An LSTM cell works as a memory to manage information according to the decisions specified by the input 
 <bold>I</bold>, output 
 <bold>Y</bold>, and forget gates 
 <bold>F</bold>. Each memory cell is implemented as shown below. 
